data.content:
Here are the improved assertions using MSTest's built-in methods:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any());              // or CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty() in newer MSTest

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)); // no built-in predicate version; this is acceptable

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);         // gives "Expected:3 Actual:5" on failure

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsTrue(x.Any())` or check count | Clearer intent |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Failure message shows expected vs actual |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Explicit null-check message on failure |

**The big win** is `Assert.AreEqual` — when it fails you get `Expected:<3> Actual:<5>` instead of just `Assert.IsTrue failed`, which makes debugging far easier.

> **Note:** MSTest's `CollectionAssert` class also offers `Contains`, `AllItemsAreUnique`, `IsSubsetOf`, and `AreEquivalent` for comparing two collections regardless of order.
